SIMPLE: warble
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Warble
<hw>War"ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf.
<er>Wormil</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Far.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A small, hard tumor
which is produced on the back of a horse by the heat or pressure of the
saddle in traveling.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A small tumor produced by
the larvae of the gadfly in the backs of horses, cattle, etc. Called
also <altname>warblet</altname>, <altname>warbeetle</altname>,
<altname>warnles</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>See <er>Wormil</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Warble</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Warble
<hw>War"ble</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Warbled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Warbling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>werbelen</ets>, OF. <ets>werbler</ets>; of Teutonic origin; cf. G.
<ets>wirbeln</ets> to turn, to warble, D. <ets>wervelen</ets>, akin to
E. <ets>whirl</ets>. See <er>Whirl</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To sing in a trilling, quavering, or vibratory
manner; to modulate with turns or variations; to trill; <as>as, certain
birds are remarkable for <ex>warbling</ex> their songs</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To utter musically; to modulate; to carol.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If she be right invoked in <qex>warbled</qex> song.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Warbling</qex> sweet the nuptial lay.</q>
<rj><qau>Trumbull.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cause to quaver or vibrate.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧And
touch the <xex>warbled</xex> string.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Warble</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Warble
<hw>War"ble</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be quavered or
modulated; to be uttered melodiously.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such strains ne'er <qex>warble</qex> in the linnet's throat.</q>
<rj><qau>Gay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To sing in a trilling manner, or with many turns and
variations.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Birds on the branches
<xex>warbling</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To sing with sudden changes from chest to head
tones; to yodel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Warble</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Warble
<hw>War"ble</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A quavering modulation of the
voice; a musical trill; a song.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And he, the wondrous child,⟦br⟧
Whose silver <qex>warble</qex> wild⟦br⟧
Outvalued every pulsing sound.</q> <rj><qau>Emerson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Warbler</ent>⟦br⟧
